Question: Which of the following statements about glycosides is false?
Answer1: Natural enzymes like emulsin, hydrolyze only the beta forms.
Answer2: Glycone refers to the sugar component, and aglycone is the non-sugar component.
Answer3: They are acetals in which the OH of the sugar is condensed with the hydroxyl group of the non-sugar component
Answer4: Both alpha- and beta- glycosides occur in nature.
CorrectExplanation: Both alpha- and beta- glycosides exist, but only the beta form occurs in nature.

Question: Which of the following statements are correct?I.  Phenylketonuria is the first discovered aminoacidopathy. II.  Alkaptonuria, also known as black urine disease, ismanifested as crippling arthritis later in life.III. The most common cause of albinism 2is an interruption in thefunctioning of the tyrosinase enzyme, which synthesizesmelanin from tyrosine.IV. Maple syrup urine disease is characterized by the buildup ofamino acids valine, isoleucine, and leucine, which block thebrain transporters for other amino acids and thus lead tomental retardation.V. All artificial sweeteners are contraindicated for   phenylketonurics.
CorrectExplanation:
STATEMENT

COMMENT

I

INCORRECT. The first discovered aminoacidopathy is alkaptonuria.

II

CORRECT. Alkaptonuria, also known as “black urine disease”, is manifested as crippling arthritis later in life.

III

CORRECT. The most common cause of albinism is an interruption in the functioning of the tyrosinase enzyme, which synthesizes melanin from Tyrosine.

IV

CORRECT. Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is characterized by the buildup of amino acids V (valine), I (isoleucine), and L (leucine), which block the brain transporters for other amino acids and thus lead to mental retardation.

V

INCORRECT. Only Aspartame is contraindicated for phenylketonurics.
IncorrectExplanation:
STATEMENT

COMMENT

I

INCORRECT. The first discovered aminoacidopathy is alkaptonuria.

II

CORRECT. Alkaptonuria, also known as “black urine disease”, is manifested as crippling arthritis later in life.

III

CORRECT. The most common cause of albinism is an interruption in the functioning of the tyrosinase enzyme, which synthesizes melanin from Tyrosine.

IV

CORRECT. Maple syrup urine disease (MSUD) is characterized by the buildup of amino acids V (valine), I (isoleucine), and L (leucine), which block the brain transporters for other amino acids and thus lead to mental retardation.

V

INCORRECT. Only Aspartame is contraindicated for phenylketonurics.

Question: Which of the following statements are incorrect? I.  Malate-aspartate shuttle produces more ATP than the glycerolphosphate shuttle.II. Question: Which of the following statements are correct? I.  Pyruvate is converted to ethanol through a one-stepconversion via pyruvate decarboxylase.II. Question: Which of the following statements are incorrect?I.   Without oxidative phosphorylation, the net energy yield ofglycolysis is 5 ATP.II.  Glycolysis is composed of two phases – the energy investmentand energy payoff phase, with 6 steps and 4 steps,respectively.III. Gluconeogenesis is exactly like glycolysis, but in reverse. IV. The most important enzyme in glycolysis is thephosphofructokinase.V.  Glycolysis is a cytosolic process that is stimulated by the insulinhormone during the fed state.
CorrectExplanation:
STATEMENT

COMMENT

I

INCORRECT. With only substrate level phosphorylation, the net energy yield of glycolysis is 2 ATP.

II

INCORRECT. GLYCOLYSIS consists of two phases: the energy investment phase and the energy payoff phase, each comprising five (5) steps.

III

INCORRECT. Gluconeogenesis includes several irreversible steps catalyzed by enzymes that are not involved in glycolysis.

IV

CORRECT. The most important enzyme in glycolysis is the phosphofructokinase.

V

CORRECT. Glycolysis is a cytosolic process that is stimulated by the insulin hormone during the fed state.
IncorrectExplanation:
STATEMENT

COMMENT

I

INCORRECT. With only substrate level phosphorylation, the net energy yield of glycolysis is 2 ATP.

II

INCORRECT. GLYCOLYSIS consists of two phases: the energy investment phase and the energy payoff phase, each comprising five (5) steps.

III

INCORRECT. Gluconeogenesis includes several irreversible steps catalyzed by enzymes that are not involved in glycolysis.

IV

CORRECT. The most important enzyme in glycolysis is the phosphofructokinase.

V

CORRECT. Glycolysis is a cytosolic process that is stimulated by the insulin hormone during the fed state.

Question: Analyze and select the underlying principle in the Millon’s test for proteins.
Answer1: Based on the reaction of cupric ions of the reagent with the N of the peptide bonds, forming a purple or violet colored complex.
Answer2: Based on the nitration of proteins, which leads to the formation of a yellow precipitate that turns to orange on treatment with an alkali.
Answer3: Based on the reaction between the phenolic group of a protein with mercuric sulfate in the presence of sodium nitrite and sulfuric acid resulting in the formation of a red colored solution.
Answer4: Based on the reaction between the reagent and the amino group of the free amino acid of the test sample, which leads to the oxidation of the compound and its deamination and resulting in the formation of deep blue colored solution.
CorrectExplanation:
TEST FOR PROTEINS

UNDERLYING PRINCIPLES

Biuret Test

Based on the reaction of cupric ions of the reagent with the N of the peptide bonds, forming a purple or violet colored complex.

Xanthoproteic Test

Based on the nitration of proteins, which leads to the formation of a yellow precipitate that turns to orange on treatment with an alkali.

Millon’s Test

Based on the reaction between the phenolic group of a protein with mercuric sulfate in the presence of sodium nitrite and sulfuric acid resulting in the formation of a red colored solution.

Ninhydrin Test

Based on the reaction between the reagent and the amino group of the free amino acid of the test sample, which leads to the oxidation of the compound and its deamination and resulting in the formation of deep blue colored solution.
IncorrectExplanation:
TEST FOR PROTEINS

UNDERLYING PRINCIPLES

Biuret Test

Based on the reaction of cupric ions of the reagent with the N of the peptide bonds, forming a purple or violet colored complex.

Xanthoproteic Test

Based on the nitration of proteins, which leads to the formation of a yellow precipitate that turns to orange on treatment with an alkali.

Millon’s Test

Based on the reaction between the phenolic group of a protein with mercuric sulfate in the presence of sodium nitrite and sulfuric acid resulting in the formation of a red colored solution.

Ninhydrin Test

Based on the reaction between the reagent and the amino group of the free amino acid of the test sample, which leads to the oxidation of the compound and its deamination and resulting in the formation of deep blue colored solution.

Question: Which of the following is the best pair of Calvin Cycle?
CorrectExplanation:
PROCESS

REACTION TO CALVIN CYCLE

EVALUATION

GLYCOLYSIS

Glycolysis is a metabolic pathway that breaks down glucose into pyruvate, producing ATP and NADH. It occurs in the cytoplasm and is part of cellular respiration.

Not directly related to the Calvin Cycle, which is part of photosynthesis and occurs in chloroplasts.

GLUCONEOGENESIS

Gluconeogenesis is the synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors. It mainly occurs in the liver and kidneys and is part of maintaining blood sugar levels.

Somewhat related as it also deals with glucose, but not directly linked to the Calvin Cycle.

PHOTOSYNTHESIS

The Calvin Cycle is a part of photosynthesis, specifically the light-independent reactions where CO2 is fixed into glucose. The light-dependent reactions produce the ATP and NADPH used.

Directly related. The Calvin Cycle is a component of the larger process of photosynthesis.

LIPOGENESIS

Lipogenesis is the process of converting acetyl-CoA to fatty acids, which then form triglycerides. It is part of lipid metabolism and occurs in the cytoplasm.

Not directly related to the Calvin Cycle. Deals with lipid synthesis rather than carbohydrate metabolism.

Question: Which of the following product may be used in Gluconeogenesis?
CorrectExplanation:
PRODUCT

RELATION TO GLUCONEOGENESIS

EVALUATION

Lactate is converted to pyruvate by lactate dehydrogenase. Pyruvate is a key substrate for gluconeogenesis, which is then converted to glucose.

Directly involved in gluconeogenesis as it can be converted into pyruvate.

CITRATE

Citrate is an intermediate in the citric acid cycle (Krebs cycle). It is not directly used in gluconeogenesis but can influence the cycle through metabolic pathways.

Not directly involved in gluconeogenesis but related through broader metabolic processes.

TARTRATE

Tartrate is not involved in major metabolic pathways like gluconeogenesis. It is more commonly known as a component in some food additives and pharmaceuticals.

Not related to gluconeogenesis.

SULFATE

Sulfate is an anion derived from sulfuric acid and is involved in various biological processes including sulfation reactions but not in gluconeogenesis.

Not related to gluconeogenesis.

Question: Which sugar when tested for its identity will give the profile below:Molisch: violet coloration Fehling’s: brick red ppt Bial’s: brown solution Seliwanoff’s: faint pink solution Mucic Acid Test: soluble crystals
CorrectExplanation:
• Molisch (+): positive for all CHO
  • Fehling’s (+): NONreducing sugars (i.e. trehalose) are eliminated
  • Bial’s (-): positive for pentoses (i.e. ribose)
  • Seliiwanoff’s (-): positive for ketoses (i.e. Fructose)
  • Mucic Acid Test (-): positive for galactose; glucose gives similar reaction BUT crystals are soluble
IncorrectExplanation:
• Molisch (+): positive for all CHO
  • Fehling’s (+): NONreducing sugars (i.e. trehalose) are eliminated
  • Bial’s (-): positive for pentoses (i.e. ribose)
  • Seliiwanoff’s (-): positive for ketoses (i.e. Fructose)
  • Mucic Acid Test (-): positive for galactose; glucose gives similar reaction BUT crystals are soluble

Question: Splicing is a post-transcriptional process that removes exons while binding the remaining the intron portions. Either capping or polyadenylation is done to the spliced mRNA to produce a mature mRNA strand.
Answer1: Only the first statement is incorrect.
Answer2: Only the second statement is incorrect.
CorrectExplanation:
Splicing removes INTRONS and binds remaining EXONS (coding portions).


A spliced mRNA is still prone to hydrolysis and degradation which is why it is capped (to protect 5’ end), AND polyadenylated (to protect 3’ end) to produce a mature mRNA.
IncorrectExplanation:
Splicing removes INTRONS and binds remaining EXONS (coding portions).


A spliced mRNA is still prone to hydrolysis and degradation which is why it is capped (to protect 5’ end), AND polyadenylated (to protect 3’ end) to produce a mature mRNA.

Question: Given the sequence AUGUCUUAUAGAGGGUAA, what mutation happens when the last guanine in the sequence is replaced by adenine?Note: UCU: Serine UAU: Tyrosine AGA: Arginine GGG: Glycine GGA: Glycine
CorrectExplanation: Since the last G belongs to the triplet GGG (glycine), replacing it with A will yield GGA (still glycine) signifying a silent result. Since a purine (G) is replaced by another purine (A), it counts as transition.
IncorrectExplanation: Since the last G belongs to the triplet GGG (glycine), replacing it with A will yield GGA (still glycine) signifying a silent result. Since a purine (G) is replaced by another purine (A), it counts as transition.

Question: Most common form of DNA
CorrectExplanation:
• B form: Most DNA is in the B form. This so-called B-DNA (see here) is a right-handed helix. It predominates in an aqueous environment like that found in cells.
  • A form: A polynucleotide in the A form is a right-handed helix, too. The A form is found in double-stranded RNA and in DNA-RNA hybrids.
  • Z form: Z-DNA is a left-handed helix found in polynucleotides with alternating purines and pyrimidines in each strand.
IncorrectExplanation:
• B form: Most DNA is in the B form. This so-called B-DNA (see here) is a right-handed helix. It predominates in an aqueous environment like that found in cells.
  • A form: A polynucleotide in the A form is a right-handed helix, too. The A form is found in double-stranded RNA and in DNA-RNA hybrids.
  • Z form: Z-DNA is a left-handed helix found in polynucleotides with alternating purines and pyrimidines in each strand.
